
===================================
📌 1. Finglish Version (Persian Latin Script)
===================================

📖 **Tashrih:**
    Dastoor `hp-pkservice` baraye modiriyat va kar ba Printer Key Service (PKS) dar system-haye HP estefade mishavad. PKS yek rahe hal baraye amniat printer ast ke estefade az printer-ha ra ba password ya credential-haye amne moratab mikonad.

⚙️ **Gozine-ha:**
    🔹 `hp-pkservice --enable`  --> ✅ PKS ra fa'al mikonad.
    🔹 `hp-pkservice --disable` --> ⛔️ PKS ra gheyre fa'al mikonad.
    🔹 `hp-pkservice --status`  --> ℹ️ Vaziyat (status) PKS ra neshon midahad (fa'al ya gheyre fa'al).
    🔹 `hp-pkservice --configure` --> ⚙️ Peykare-bandi (configure) PKS ra rah andazi mikonad.

🛠 **Mesal-ha:**

    $ hp-pkservice --status

    🔹 Vaziyat PKS ra neshon midahad.

    $ sudo hp-pkservice --enable

    🔹 PKS ra fa'al mikonad (be dastresi root niaz darad).

✅ **Mesal sade:**

    $ hp-pkservice --status
    PKS is currently: Enabled

    🔹  In mesal neshon midahad ke PKS dar hal hazer fa'al ast.

===================================
📌 2. English Version
===================================

📖 **Description:**
    The `hp-pkservice` command is used to manage and interact with the Printer Key Service (PKS) on HP systems. PKS is a printer security solution that controls access to printers using passwords or secure credentials.

⚙️ **Options:**
    🔹 `hp-pkservice --enable`  --> ✅ Enables PKS.
    🔹 `hp-pkservice --disable` --> ⛔️ Disables PKS.
    🔹 `hp-pkservice --status`  --> ℹ️ Shows the status of PKS (enabled or disabled).
    🔹 `hp-pkservice --configure` --> ⚙️ Launches the PKS configuration utility.

🛠 **Examples:**

    $ hp-pkservice --status

    🔹 Shows the current status of PKS.

    $ sudo hp-pkservice --enable

    🔹 Enables PKS (requires root privileges).

✅ **Simple Example:**

    $ hp-pkservice --status
    PKS is currently: Enabled

    🔹 This example shows that PKS is currently enabled.

